    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hi, i'm in the middle of buying my first house in austin and i'm a bit confused. my realtor mentioned my earnest money is being held in an escrow account. can u explain what that actually means and why they don't just give it to the seller right away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Earnest money is a deposit you put down to show the seller you are serious about buying the house. It's held in an escrow account, which is like a neutral, secure holding place managed by a third party, like your title company. This prevents either you or the seller from taking the money before all the deal contingencies, like inspections, are met. If the sale goes through, the earnest money is usually applied toward your down payment; if it falls through due to a valid reason, you might get it back.",
